result.execSummary:
Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Daren W Dent in court with attorney Kari S. Hoel.   James D. Babbitt appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  This matter came on before the court for a plea and sentencing.   Hearing called to order at 1:27 p.m.   Case hearing along with 16CF122 and 16CF127.    Attorney Babbitt cited the plea agreement as indicated on the case settlement filed with the Court.   Court informs the defendant of his rights.  Defendant understands his rights.  Defendant enters a plea of Guilty to two misdemeanor theft charges as indicated on the case settlement.   Other charges were dismissed but read in for sentencing purposes.   Court finds factual basis and finds defendant understand his plea and his rights.   Court finds defendant guilty of two misdemeanor thefts.  Court  quashes warrant issued this AM.   Court orders sentence as proposed in case settlement.    Hearing adjourned at 1:39 a.m.
